# Emily Plugin & Tool Rules

## BaseTool Contract
Every tool must subclass `BaseTool` from `plugins/base.py` and implement:
- `name: str` — unique tool identifier
- `description: str` — what the tool does (used in LLM tool-calling prompts)
- `parameters: dict` — JSON Schema for input validation
- `async execute(params, context) -> ToolResult` — the actual operation
- `async dry_run(params) -> str` — explain what would happen without doing it (MANDATORY)

## Required Metadata
- `requires_approval: bool` — set True for destructive or sensitive operations (file writes, shell commands, process management, network requests)
- `timeout_seconds: int` — maximum execution time before auto-cancellation
- `rate_limit: RateLimit` — calls per minute/hour limits

## File Organization
- Built-in tools live in `plugins/builtin/`
- Generated tools (created by ToolBuilderAgent) live in `plugins/generated/`
- Generated tools are NEVER auto-loaded — they require explicit user approval before first use
- One tool class per file, filename matches the tool name (snake_case)

## Validation
- Override `async validate(params) -> ValidationResult` for custom parameter checks
- Always call `self.validate()` before execution (or use `safe_execute()` which does this)
- Return `ValidationResult.fail("reason")` for invalid params, never raise exceptions in validate

## Execution
- Always use `ToolResult.ok(output)` and `ToolResult.fail(error)` — never return raw dicts
- Catch and handle exceptions inside `execute()` — unhandled exceptions are caught by `safe_execute()` but should be avoided
- Respect `context.sandbox_enabled` and `context.allowed_paths` for filesystem operations
- Log tool invocations via structlog for the audit trail

## Testing
- Every tool must have at least one unit test in `tests/unit/`
- Test both `execute()` and `dry_run()` methods
- Test validation with both valid and invalid parameters
- Mock external dependencies (HTTP, filesystem, subprocess) at the boundary
